that the same parts of the right hemisphere light up when observing sign language, as when observing other gestures such as movement of hands, body, or face. However, when observing sign language in particular, the Wernicke’s area also lights up, (it doesn’t light up when just a random gesture is perceived). This implies that, just as the brain is able to distinguish between sound and language, the brain is able to assign some specific linguistic meaning to gestures and then differentiate between linguistic gestures and just regular ones. %0a%3c %0a%3c All of this together implies that the brain is “specialized in language per se, not [just] in speaking” (Patrick C. Trettenbrein of MPI CBS). Overall, this has taught me a lot about the brain and shown that sign and spoken language are more similar than I previously thought.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c %0a%3c https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2021/02/210219124236.htm%0a%3c %0a%3c https://theconversation.com/what-sign-language-teaches-us-about-the-brain-29628#:~:text=More%2520videos%2520on%2520YouTube,-Switch%2520camera&text=If%2520Broca's%2520area%2520is%2520involved,%252C%2520surprisingly%252C%2520they%2520do%2520not.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
